node.text:
Over the holiday weekend, five @MBK_Alliance youth from the South Side of Chicago traveled to Big Sky, Montana, to shadow industry professionals to see what it takes to run a live broadcast of a premier golf event like #TheMatch. They even got the chance to meet Tom Brady, Aaron Rodgers, Phil Mickelson, and Bryson DeChambeau!

Too often, young people of color are faced with persistent opportunity gaps, hindering their ability to gain unique industry skills and make important connections to advance their future careers. That’s why we’re especially grateful to Turner Sports for making this exciting experience possible for these young men.

node.title: MBK Youth Attend The Match in Montana

After a tough year and half of teaching through a pandemic, South Shore High School educator Monique Thorpe was overjoyed to get a surprise phone call from President @BarackObama. She even introduced him to her 90-year-old mother.

Following their chat, the President surprised Ms. Thorpe’s students with a virtual class drop-in. Together they discussed the Obama Presidential Center and the ways in which the Center will benefit young people across Chicago.

"I’m excited about the impact that the Obama Presidential Center can have on the South Side of Chicago. I think about how can we, as small business owners, be a part of this?” —Eric Williams, owner of @TheSilverRoom

Get a glimpse into @BarackObama’s recent conversation with @i_know_eric, as they discuss the economic benefits of the Center, their collective hopes for the neighborhood, and Eric’s newest South Side venture.

node.text: Every #PrideMonth, we reflect on the significant progress that has been made on the long road towards equality for LGBTQ Americans. A seminal moment in that journey happened in June 2015 when the U.S. Supreme Court handed down a landmark decision that legalized same-sex marriage. With that ruling, love won—same-sex marriage bans across the country were struck down.

Sports can be transformative in young people’s lives—giving them space to express themselves and be part of something bigger. Someone who believes in the power of sports is @SouthSide_WolfPack Coach Ernest Radcliffe.

During a recent call, Coach Radcliffe invited President @BarackObama to stop by one of their practices in Jackson Park—the future home of the Obama Presidential Center. Eager to see the team in action, the President made a surprise visit earlier this week.

To mark #InternationalMuseumDay, we’re giving audiences a closer look at our plans for the Obama Presidential Center and how we’re reimagining what a twenty-first century museum looks like. 

A key part of our work is identifying artifacts for inclusion in the Museum. In keeping with President and Mrs. Obama’s belief that change happens from the bottom up, we’ve hosted community collection events in Chicago, Iowa, and Hawaiʻi to discover some of the objects that will inform the Museum’s collection and hear the stories of the people who held onto them.

In this video you can hear directly from Chicagoans who came out to Stony Island Arts Bank on the South Side and shared their stories of the Obamas that date back long before their time in the White House. #IMD2021

Before the Obama Presidential Center can break ground later this year, important preparatory work must be done by the City of Chicago.

Today, we’re excited to announce that that work is beginning, marking the official start of our road to groundbreaking. Hear from President @BarackObama, @chicagosmayor, and other Chicago officials on the significant economic impact the Center will have on the South Side of Chicago.

node.title: City Preparatory Work Begins Ahead of OPC Groundbreaking

Happy #LeftHandersDay!

"Hope requires action." —@BarackObama

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Obama Foundation in Chicago, Illinois. May be an image of 7 people, people standing and outdoors.

node.text:
As part of our celebrations for President Obama's birthday, you helped us give him the best gift: Your story. We asked you to share how you’ve spent 60 minutes—or even 60 seconds—giving back to your communities—and you didn’t disappoint.

We heard from over 1,300 people from nearly every continent about how they’ve served their communities. One of those stories came from Richard K. from Chicago. Richard has been volunteering his time with the faith community of Saint Sabina, distributing COVID-19 protection kits, packaging free food, delivering “grow your own grocery kits”, and raising awareness for the Stein Learning Gardens and food insecurity in Auburn Gresham neighborhood.

Want to read more inspiring stories in honor of President Obama’s 60th birthday? Visit the link in our bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Obama Foundation on August 04, 2021. May be an image of 6 people, child, people standing and indoor.

node.text:
🎉 Happy Birthday, @BarackObama!
 
President Obama has always enjoyed hearing about the good work people are doing to make a positive impact. This year, give him the ultimate 60th birthday gift by sharing how you've spent 60 minutes—or even 60 seconds—giving back to your community.

Visit the link in our bio to add your voice!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Obama Foundation on August 02, 2021. May be an image of 10 people, people standing and indoor.

node.text:
From the start, we here at the Obama Foundation have worked to build a diverse network of emerging leaders, in our hometown of Chicago and around the world, because we believe that real change happens when ordinary people come together to make a difference.

As we kick off President Obama's birthday week, get inspired by getting to know 60 talented leaders in our network who are paving the way for a brighter future—and if you can, pitch in $6 or $60 to support their work as they turn their hope into meaningful action.

🎉  Visit the link in our bio for more details.

node.text:
Storytelling can help us understand experiences that are not our own and inspire others to take meaningful action. That’s why we are so proud of Obama Fellow Zarlasht Halaimzai, who recently penned a vulnerable and powerful reflection about her family’s journey of fleeing Afghanistan to resettle in the United Kingdom.

“It has taken me a long time to write about my experience of arriving in the UK as a refugee,” Zarlasht said. “It’s painful and personal. But I felt that maybe helping people to understand would stimulate something other than this terrible hostility towards refugees and Afghans.”

After resettling, Zarlasht and her family faced hostility from neighbors, blatant xenophobia, and unprovoked violent attacks.

“It’s difficult to describe the feeling of dislocation. People who are born in places that protect them from the misery of displacement find it hard to understand,” Zarlasht explained.

Almost three decades after fleeing Afghanistan, Zarlasht now runs the @refugeetrauma, a charity in Greece that works with refugees to help overcome trauma, pain, and anxiety while navigating the asylum process.

Read Zarlasht’s full piece by visiting the link in our bio.

One year ago, the world lost two Civil Rights icons on the same day—Representative John Lewis and Reverend C.T. Vivian. 

At the Obama Foundation, our work is to inspire the next generation of leaders so that they can create a better world. Both Lewis and Vivian embodied that mission throughout their years, and though we mourn the tremendous loss, we are lifted by their legacies—empowering young people to take up the baton of justice for years to come.
